{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":36187,"record_hash":"sha256:dd011265d1aae43ab01571fbd73659199f6c0a47b8c7b6bb72b08f101a7c1e61","timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:35:48.563Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: b306af\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1670\nOutput:\n# Future Use Cases\n\nThis document records the product direction the first agentlog POC should point\ntoward. These use cases are not implemented end to end by the POC, but they\nshape the data model.\n\n## 1. Session Handoff\n\nA developer starts an agent session on one machine and wants to continue it on\nanother machine, possibly with another agent.\n\nExamples:\n\n- Claude Code starts the planning locally, then OpenClaw continues on a remote\n  machine where the repository is already available.\n- OpenClaw starts work on a remote machine, then the user continues locally so\n  they can run a desktop app or device-specific tests.\n\nFor this to work later, GitButler needs to capture enough session context into\nGitMeta, move that metadata through Git transport, and expose it on the other\nside in a form that another agent can use. The POC can sync after hook capture,\nbut it does not resume a session; its project-scoped session records should be\ndurable enough to make that possible.\n\nExpected access pattern:\n\n1. fetch or otherwise exchange GitMeta data for the repository\n2. read `gitbutler:agent-sessions` from the `project` target\n3. choose a session, either by recency, user selection, or a future explicit\n   relationship\n4. read `gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:transcript`\n5. reconstruct useful context from `kind`, `role`, `text`, `tool_name`,\n   `tool_input`, `source_event_kind`, and redacted `source_record`\n6. sort records by transcript fields rather than relying on stored GitMeta list\n   order\n\nThat means the transcript list must be readable without knowing the original\nmachine's file paths, working-directory state, branch state, or raw provider\nsession id.\n\nThe POC points at contextual handoff, not exact native session replay. Resuming\ninside the same provider as if the original transcript file still existed may\nneed a later native-transcript artifact or provider-specific reconstruction\nflow.\n\n## 2. Sharing Se\n[TRUNCATED]\nated with many branch or review objects\n- many sessions associated with one branch or review object\n- branch or commit associations being added after capture\n\n## POC Direction\n\nThe first POC should:\n\n- write redacted, shareable-ready `gitbutler:*` keys\n- keep session data on the `project` target\n- allow optional explicit target association without inference\n- use a durable session key independent of branches and commits\n- keep source metadata separate from per-record transcript records\n- keep enough normalized fields to support timeline browsing without reparsing\n  every provider-specific record\n- avoid storing local paths, working-directory values, branches, or raw provider\n  session ids\n- avoid branch inference and PR association\n\nThe POC should not try to solve session merging. A future UX can decide whether\nmultiple provider sessions should be joined into one GitButler-level session.\n\n## Deduplication\n\nUse stable record hashes:\n\n```text\nsha256(trimmed raw JSONL line bytes)\n```\n\nCapture checks `:record-hashes` before appending transcript records. The\ntranscript list remains the append-friendly storage value; the hash set is the\ncompact dedupe index. Re-running capture against the same transcript is a no-op\nunless the transcript grew.\n\n## Association Model\n\nDo not attach transcript data directly to branches, commits, changes, or pull\nrequests in the POC. The project session is the durable object.\n\nWhen capture is given an explicit association target, write only this\nrelationship reference:\n\n```text\n<branch/change/commit target>\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nSee [Future Use Cases](future-use-cases.md) for access patterns and product\nmotivation.\n\n## Publication\n\nThe POC writes shareable-ready keys. `but agentlog sync` is the exchange step\nand uses GitMeta's configured metadata remote behavior. Hook capture starts that\nsame command in the background after a successful capture. Sync is not scoped to\nthe `gitbutler:*` agentlog keys, so it may exchange other shareable GitMeta\nmetadata too.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:35:48.563Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}